I just didn't like the puzzles maybe.

221
00:12:00,399 --> 00:12:02,200
Schafer: Puzzles.

222
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:04,600
So you would say you would never
advocate a game that had puzzles in it?

223
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:06,333
Wolpaw: No. No.

224
00:12:06,333 --> 00:12:08,100
Schafer: Like Portal, for example.

225
00:12:08,100 --> 00:12:09,899
Schafer: One of the big
questions was whether or not

226
00:12:09,899 --> 00:12:12,066
games should have puzzles
in them, in adventure games.

227
00:12:12,066 --> 00:12:17,133
That came up when we were talking to
the Super Brothers, Craig and Chris.

228
00:12:17,133 --> 00:12:20,899
About Sword and Sorcery, about how
when they played the old adventure games

229
00:12:20,899 --> 00:12:23,233
the thing that didn't hold
up for them was the puzzles,

230
00:12:23,233 --> 00:12:25,333
because there were
these blocks to the flow.

231
00:12:25,333 --> 00:12:27,000
They really wanted the flow to happen.

232
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:30,866
Adams: And actually those types of
mechanics, that sort of inventory puzzles,

233
00:12:30,866 --> 00:12:34,933
are things that I don't miss
from older adventure games.

234
00:12:34,933 --> 00:12:37,266
What I love about older
adventure games is that there's,

235
00:12:37,266 --> 00:12:39,399
you have a flow and there's
a story and there's characters.

236
00:12:39,399 --> 00:12:41,100
And it just kind of surprises you.

237
00:12:41,100 --> 00:12:43,133
And it was never figuring out, you know,

238
00:12:43,133 --> 00:12:46,866
which little pixel and which screen 
do I combine with the other.

239
00:12:46,866 --> 00:12:50,100
So, but we tried to
make it more just flow.

240
00:12:50,100 --> 00:12:52,133
Schafer: I thought about
that for a long time.

241
00:12:52,133 --> 00:12:56,033
It was like, is that, are puzzles an
antiquated, you know, notion for these games?

242
00:12:56,033 --> 00:12:58,600
Are they a block to the narrative flow?

243
00:12:58,600 --> 00:13:02,200
But I felt like in the end that wasn't
the case for the game we were making.

244
00:13:02,200 --> 00:13:04,399
I think the game they were
making was a really specific,

245
00:13:04,399 --> 00:13:06,533
like for what they wanted to make,

246
00:13:06,533 --> 00:13:09,399
it wouldn't have suited their purposes
to have a bunch of like, head scratchers.

247
00:13:09,399 --> 00:13:11,833
Piotrowski: But that was
really a challenging moment.

248
00:13:11,833 --> 00:13:13,633
It was kind of like trying to
shed some of those things that

249
00:13:13,633 --> 00:13:16,533
were like buried in our heads from
playing all these games when we were kids.

250
00:13:16,533 --> 00:13:18,766
Schafer: Like what, talking
about adventure games,

251
00:13:18,766 --> 00:13:20,733
people's memories of playing adventure
games when they were kids.

252
00:13:20,733 --> 00:13:23,033
So many of them were like, that's
the only thing I had to do that summer.

253
00:13:23,033 --> 00:13:26,533
I got stuck in my grandma's house for the summer
and I played Day of the Tentacle every day.

254
00:13:26,533 --> 00:13:31,333
Like, I mean, people have so many
options now for entertainment.

255
00:13:31,333 --> 00:13:33,500
It's going to be really
hard to make sure that

256
00:13:33,500 --> 00:13:37,166
there's something really sticky about the game
that makes them want to come back.

257
00:13:37,166 --> 00:13:39,766
I think a lot of that
is atmosphere. For me.

258
00:13:39,766 --> 00:13:43,899
Like, when I, you know, you
feel haunted by a game sometimes.

259
00:13:43,899 --> 00:13:45,833
Like you're just at your
work or you're at school

260
00:13:45,833 --> 00:13:47,933
and you think about the music
and you think about the world

261
00:13:47,933 --> 00:13:51,233
and you're like, I really, that world
feels so real that you want to go back there.

262
00:13:51,233 --> 00:13:53,299
That's the goal on it.

263
00:13:53,299 --> 00:13:55,500
You know, that's the way you keep
people playing an adventure game.

264
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:58,533
Wolpaw: So anyway, did that help?

265
00:13:58,540 --> 00:14:00,600
Is what I'm telling you helping at all?

266
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:02,600
Schafer: Don't try to improve adventure games
because they're always bad.

267
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:03,799
Just make an old bad one.

268
00:14:03,799 --> 00:14:05,100
Wolpaw: Yeah, make one
of your old bad ones.

269
00:14:05,100 --> 00:14:07,399
Schafer: Ok, good. Well, thank
you Eric Wolpaw for coming.

270
00:14:07,399 --> 00:14:11,533
And spreading your
special brand of love.

271
00:14:11,533 --> 00:14:14,866
Wolpaw: Yeah, I mean, I'm just kidding.

272
00:14:14,866 --> 00:14:17,799
I really do think the
adventure game you make

273
00:14:17,799 --> 00:14:21,359
will be about as good
as the old ones you made.

274
00:14:21,360 --> 00:14:23,827
