00:16:31,533 --> 00:16:33,299
That was the idea for the intro.

312
00:16:33,299 --> 00:16:35,633
See, he's leaning, they're leaning against
that wall and he's in a spaceship.

313
00:16:35,633 --> 00:16:37,700
And she's looking at a castle.

314
00:16:37,700 --> 00:16:39,899
Gilbert: And then you just choose then,
one you want to start with?

315
00:16:39,899 --> 00:16:41,933
Schafer: Yeah.

316
00:16:41,933 --> 00:16:43,766
Schafer: The story so far, the
reason I'm excited about it is that

317
00:16:43,766 --> 00:16:48,333
I've never done a story about this type,
like this age of character.

318
00:16:48,333 --> 00:16:50,366
Like a coming of age story.

319
00:16:50,366 --> 00:16:52,366
About a boy and a girl,
something about that

320
00:16:52,366 --> 00:16:59,366
the pairing of those like equal stories
going on at the same time.

321
00:16:59,366 --> 00:17:04,000
And the things I guess that are interesting
about that age to me are,

322
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:10,766
it's an age where you're learning to take
control and take some power in your life

323
00:17:10,766 --> 00:17:13,733
and also the responsibility
that goes along with that.

324
00:17:13,733 --> 00:17:17,366
You know, you're learning that
you have power in your life

325
00:17:17,366 --> 00:17:20,766
and you're learning you have the
power to control your destiny.

326
00:17:20,766 --> 00:17:25,133
You have the power to hurt people
and then kind of, you know,

327
00:17:25,133 --> 00:17:28,733
becoming an adult or becoming a
young adult is about learning that

328
00:17:28,733 --> 00:17:31,833
you can grab the wheel of your life
and steer it in a different direction.

329
00:17:31,833 --> 00:17:35,533
I think that's, but then you take the
responsibility for what you've done.

330
00:17:35,533 --> 00:17:38,666
And now no one's telling you,
you know, that you're going to be ok

331
00:17:38,666 --> 00:17:41,033
if you go in this direction,
because you've chosen to do it.

332
00:17:41,033 --> 00:17:43,533
Gilbert: I think it's
a really creative idea,

333
00:17:43,533 --> 00:17:48,200
but I don't think it's the kind of thing
that we want to fund at this moment.

334
00:17:49,799 --> 00:17:53,066
Schafer: That's great. That's so
funny because that's so crazy.

335
00:17:54,633 --> 00:17:56,799
Schafer: No. I mean, in some
ways it's too early for feedback.

336
00:17:56,799 --> 00:18:00,533
I mean, unless I'm totally am like,
stealing an idea from something,

337
00:18:00,533 --> 00:18:04,466
because you can't say whether an idea
is good or not in some ways in the beginning,

338
00:18:04,466 --> 00:18:09,966
because so much is about the execution 
or the specifics of like how, you know.

339
00:18:09,966 --> 00:18:13,799
Because it's kind of, it's kind
of a vague pitch in a way.

340
00:18:13,799 --> 00:18:18,366
It's like I want to do, I want to do
this game that's about two stories,

341
00:18:18,366 --> 00:18:22,433
about a boy and a girl 
in really separate different worlds

342
00:18:22,433 --> 00:18:25,599
who are navigating this
space in between them.

343
00:18:25,599 --> 00:18:28,566
You know, like that could
mean a lot of different things.

344
00:18:28,566 --> 00:18:30,299
That could be told many different ways.

345
00:18:30,299 --> 00:18:32,633
So it's really hard for anyone to
say like, oh, that's a good idea.

346
00:18:32,633 --> 00:18:36,000
But I mean, because I do
have, you do have some idea

347
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:40,333
of how you're going to do it
but you can't articulate all of it.

348
00:18:47,366 --> 00:18:50,200
Schafer: I'm ready for you.

